ARMA models & Stationarity

  1. \(ARMA(p,q)\) w/ drift & trend: \(\ X_t=\mu+\delta t+\Sigma_{i=1}^p \theta_iX_{t-i}+\varepsilon_t+\Sigma_{j=1}^p \phi_j\varepsilon_{t-j}\)
  2. Weakly stationarity:
    • \(\mathbb{E}(X_t) \perp t, \forall t\)
    • \(\text{Cov}(X_t,X_{t+l})=\gamma(l) \perp t, \forall t\)
    • trend stationary: stationary after detrending
  3. (2.) for \(ARMA(p,q)\) guaranteed by \(\Sigma_{i=1}^p |\theta_i|<1\)
  4. \(ADF\) tests (3.), selecting \(p, q\) with \(AIC\):
  5. \(AIC=-2\ln L(p,q)+2(p+q+2+\mathbf{1}_{\delta\neq 0})\rightarrow \min_{p,q}\)

ADF test for stationarity

  • Battery & Criminal SA
    • weakly stationary at \(0.1\%\) level
    • 1 lag selected by AIC
  • Assault & Robbery
    • trend stationary at \(0.1\%\) level
    • significant negative time trend
    • 1 lag selected by AIC

Chosen ARMA models (using AIC):

  • Battery: \(\text{ARMA}(1^{0.1\%},1^{0.1\%})\), w/o trend

\(X_t=192.2-0.999X_{t-1}+\varepsilon_t+0.978\varepsilon_{t-1}\)

  • Assault: MA(\(1^{10\%}\)) w/ trend\(^{0.1\%}\)

\(X_t=29.1-0.107t+\varepsilon_t-0.178\varepsilon_{t-1}\)

  • Robbery: MA(\(1^{0.1\%}\)) w/ trend\(^{1\%}\)

\(X_t=17.5-0.071t+\varepsilon_t+0.49\varepsilon_{t-1}\)

  • Criminal SA: AR(\(1^{>10\%}\)) w/o trend

\(X_t=7.76+0.1X_{t-1}+\varepsilon_t\)
